Set a compass to a length between 9 to 12 inches (23 to 30 cm), depending on the size of the wearer's head. Place the point of the compass in the middle of the bottom edge and draw a half-circle using the attached pencil. Cut this shape out with scissors after drawing it. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/12/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/12/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The exact size of your hat should vary based on the size of the intended wearer. For a toddler or young child, make the radius 9 or 10 inches (23 or 25 cm) long. For a slightly older child, use a radius of 11 or 12 (28 or 30 cm) inches. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/04/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/04/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

On a new sheet of construction paper, draw a line that is equal in length to the diameter of hat's opening. Draw a circle around this line, then draw a bigger circle around that. Cut out the larger circle and the smaller circle, and use the large ring left behind as your brim. Measure the inside diameter of your cone several times and at several places. Use the smallest measurement you get when deciding on the diameter of your brim. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/31/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/31/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

When drawing the inner circle of your brim, place the pointed end of the compass on the midpoint of your diameter line and set the compass to half the diameter's length. Draw around the line, making sure that your perimeter touches both ends of the line. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2b/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2b/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

After drawing the inner circle, set the compass so that your new radius is 3 inches (7.6 cm) larger than the radius of your inner circle. Use the same center point and draw a larger circle evenly around the smaller inner circle. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bd/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bd/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You can discard the inner circle after cutting them both out. You only need the outer ring for your brim. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/85/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/85/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Slide the brim over the top of the hat and onto the fringes at the base. Glue or tape the brim to these fringes from the underside. The brim should fit snugly on the fringes of the cone. If you cannot slide it all the way down to these fringes, however, carefully cut away extra paper from the inside ring of the brim and try again. Repeat as needed until the brim lies flat on top of the flaps. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The easiest way to attach the brim to the fringes of the hat is to apply glue or double-sided tape to the bottom inner ring of the brim before sliding it onto the flaps. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/83/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/83/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you have stickers or other pre-made decorations you plan on using, skip this step. Otherwise, sketch several stars and crescent moons onto a sheet of shiny aluminum foil and cut them out using a sharp pair of scissors. If you do not want to use aluminum foil, you could use plain construction paper, instead. For an added touch, decorate plain paper embellishments with glitter or sparkly paint. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/00/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/00/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You can also paint decorations directly onto the hat instead of cutting out shapes from other material. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/85/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/85/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Unpin the trimmed interfacing and lay it flat onto your intended fabric. Pin in place, then cut out a piece of fabric that matches the outline of your interfacing exactly. Make sure that the adhesive side of the interfacing faces your fabric as you cut the fabric out. The adhesive side is usually the glossy side. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/16/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-12Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-12Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/16/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-12Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-12Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Choose a fabric type you feel comfortable working with. Synthetic satin is cost-effective and has a traditional look, but the edges can fray easily and some hemming will be required. Felt has a less traditional look, but it is both inexpensive and easy to work with since it does not fray. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/ba/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-12Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-12Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/ba/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-12Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-12Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Roll the material back into a cone and pin in it in place. Hand stitch the side of the cone using a neat back stitch. Alternatively, you could glue the edge in place with hot glue if you want a no-sew option. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0f/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-14Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-14Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0f/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-14Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-14Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you are working with a fray-resistant fabric like felt, you do not need to worry about hems. If you are using a material that frays, however, you should hem the side edges with a 1/2 inch (1.25 cm) seam allowance before rolling the hat into a cone. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1e/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-14Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-14Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1e/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-14Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-14Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Measure the opening at the base of your cone. Use a compass fitted with a fabric pencil to draw a circle of the same diameter onto a piece of interfacing. Draw a second circle around the first that is 2 to 3 inches (5 to 7.6 cm) wider. Cut out both circles so that you are left with a large ring of interfacing. Pin the interfacing to your fabric with the fusible side facing down. Cut the fabric out, as well. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5c/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-15Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-15Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5c/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-15Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-15Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Note that you should add an extra 1/2 inch (1.25 cm) to both the inside and outside of the ring if you are using material that frays, like satin. This extra fabric will be used as a seam allowance for a hem. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2d/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-15Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-15Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2d/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-15Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-15Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Slide the brim onto the hat so that the inner ring rests flat on top of the flaps at the cone's base. Hot glue or stitch each of these flaps onto the ring from the underside of the hat. Unless the bottom edge of the cone has frayed significantly, you should not need to hem it before attaching the brim. The glue or thread used to secure the brim onto the hat should prevent the lower edge from fraying, thereby negating the need for a separate hem. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/33/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-19Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-19Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/33/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-19Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-19Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

As you sew the brim onto the hat, keep your stitches as flat as possible. Do not pull the thread too tightly or the fabric will bunch up. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/46/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-19Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-19Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/46/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-19Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-19Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The basic structure of your hat is done at this point, so all you need to do is decorate it to your liking. Some ideas include:
Cut out stars and crescent moons from yellow felt and hot glue the shapes onto your hat. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7f/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7f/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cover the seam with a strip of decorative ribbon, or wrap a long piece of ribbon around the hat in a spiral. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/24/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/24/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Look for small patches, beads, or craft embellishments to glue, sew, or iron onto the hat in a random pattern. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c9/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c9/Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Wizard-Hat-Step-20Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
